docs.abstract: Wages are growing fast, but prices are rising even faster.
docs.snippet: Wages are growing fast, but prices are rising even faster.
docs.lead_paragraph: This morning, the government will report inflation data for January. Economists expect that prices continued to climb at the fastest pace in 40 years. But how much workers feel the effects of inflation depends on whether wages, which have also been growing fast, can keep pace with rising prices. docs.abstract: Regulators are expected to give Microsoft’s proposed acquisition of Activision Blizzard — the largest in Microsoft’s history — a tough review.
docs.snippet: Regulators are expected to give Microsoft’s proposed acquisition of Activision Blizzard — the largest in Microsoft’s history — a tough review.
docs.lead_paragraph: Microsoft on Wednesday kicked off a charm offensive in Washington to gain government approval for its $70 billion deal to buy the video game company Activision Blizzard, saying it would not give preferential treatment to its own games in its app stores.

headline.main: Microsoft starts a charm offensive to push through its Activision deal.

byline.original: By David McCabe and Cecilia Kang

docs.abstract: Bigger is still better, as the largest tech firms keep gobbling up weakened rivals.
docs.snippet: Bigger is still better, as the largest tech firms keep gobbling up weakened rivals.
docs.lead_paragraph: It feels like another turbulent time in tech, another paradigm shift, like what happened with the move to mobile. In this case, it is a move away from the internet as we know it (Web2) — a soft-touch regulatory environment — to what’s being called Web3, where actual guardrails might be erected.

headline.main: The Pandemic Culls the Big Tech Herd

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House on Monday overwhelmingly passed legislation that would overhaul how workplace sexual assault and harassment claims are handled, approving a significant change in employment law that would effectively do away with forced arbitration in such cases, eliminating a central source of protection for the perpetrators.

docs.abstract: Amazon, Apple, Google and Microsoft are expanding their reach over the rest of the economy.
docs.snippet: Amazon, Apple, Google and Microsoft are expanding their reach over the rest of the economy.
docs.lead_paragraph: The stock market has lately soured on the technology industry. Stock prices of many of the largest companies are down this year, some slightly — shares of Apple and Google have fallen more than 6 percent — and some stupendously: Facebook's parent company, Meta, and Netflix have lost about a third of their value since the New Year. Because surging tech stocks drove a big part of the stock market’s rise in 2021, their decline has contributed much to the market’s fall. The S & P 500 is down by about 7 percent in 2022.

headline.main: The Rise of Big Tech May Just Be Starting
